  "suggestion": "[affective-neuroscience+psycholinguistics+dimensional-emotion-theory+Russell-circumplex] IMPLEMENT NOW — Circumplex Emotion Mapping (Russell 1980). The current model produces only 6 coarse emotion labels (fear/anxiety/joy/surprise/tension/calm), causing mismatches on benchmarks expecting richer vocabulary (excitement, contentment, sadness, shame, disgust, pride, etc.). Replace the emotion heuristic with Russell's 2D valence×arousal circumplex: valence = tanh((isGain ? +1 : -1) × pe × 2) clamped to [-1,1], arousal already present as person.arousal. Map (valence, arousal) to a 3×3 grid: high-arousal+positive='excited', mid-arousal+positive='happy', low-arousal+positive='content', high-arousal+neutral='alert', neutral='neutral', low-arousal+neutral='bored', high-arousal+negative='terrified'/'angry' (split by isThreat), mid-arousal+negative='anxious'/'sad', low-arousal+negative='depressed'. This gives ~12 emotion labels, covers all benchmark domains, and adds zero new free parameters — it reuses existing pe and arousal values. — Math: valence = tanh((gain ? +1 : -1) × pe × 2); emotion = circumplex_grid[bin(arousal, 3)][bin(valence, 3)]; [opponent-process-theory+dynamical-systems+cognitive-dissonance+approach-avoidance-conflict] IMPLEMENT NOW — Multi-Need Opponent Process Conflict Resolver. The current model selects ONE dominant need and produces a single clean emotion+behavior. But most interesting psychological phenomena — ambivalence, approach-avoidance, cognitive dissonance, mixed emotions — arise when two needs produce high competing free energy. Add: after computing all F values, if F_second / F_first > 0.65, treat as 'need conflict'. Conflict resolution rules: (safety vs autonomy) → ambivalence/freeze; (belonging vs esteem) → performance-anxiety if threat, pride if gain; (achievement vs fairness) → guilt or envy; (autonomy vs belonging) → loneliness or rebellion. Blend emotions as '{emotion1}-{emotion2}' compound (e.g. 'anxious-excited'). Set behavior to the conflict-specific resolution. This directly explains cognitive dissonance, FOMO, moral conflict, and bittersweet phenomena with ~30 lines of code and no new parameters. — Math: conflict_ratio = F_second / F_first; if ratio > 0.65: blend(emotion1, emotion2), override behavior with conflict_table[need1][need2]; [narrative-psychology+dynamical-systems+attractor-theory+literary-theory+McAdams-identity] Narrative Attractor State Engine (McAdams Narrative Identity + Dynamical Systems). Current model treats each prediction as stateless — the same stimulus always produces the same response regardless of a person's self-narrative. But McAdams (1993) shows people organize experience around a persistent 'personal myth' that acts as a strange attractor in behavioral space: Hero (agency-seeking, overcomes), Seeker (exploration-driven), Victim (helplessness-reinforcing), Caretaker (other-focused), Rebel (autonomy-maximizing). Implement: detect narrative type from person.history tokens; compute 'narrative completion pull' — how much would each possible behavior advance the person's narrative arc toward its canonical resolution? Behavior = argmax(free_energy_reduction + narrative_momentum). Math: narrative_momentum = dot(behavior_vector, archetype_completion_vector) where vectors are sparse keyword bags. This explains why two people with identical needs respond differently to the same stimulus — their narrative attractor differs. Testable: a person with victim-history predicts helplessness even under moderate threat (low pe), while a hero-history predicts approach. — Math: narrative_pull(b) = cos_sim(behavior_keywords(b), archetype_completion(narrative_type)); final_behavior = argmax(F_reduction + λ × narrative_pull)",
